{"title_page": "Ulrika Jonsson", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name       = Ulrika Jonsson\n| birth_name = Eva Jonsson<ref name=biop1>{{harv|Jonsson|2003|p=1}}</ref>\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1967|8|16|df=y}}<ref name=biop1/>\n| birth_place = [[Sollentuna Municipality|Sollentuna]], Sweden\n| nationality = Swedish, English\n| other_names = Ulrika Johnson\n| residence = [[South Moreton]], [[Oxfordshire]], England\n| occupation = Actress, television presenter, journalist, novelist\n| television  = ''[[TV-am]]'' (1989\u20131992)<br>''[[Gladiators (1992 UK TV series)|Gladiators]]'' (1992\u20132000)<br>''[[Shooting Stars (TV series)|Shooting Stars]]'' (1995\u20132002, 2009\u20132011)<br>''[[Eurovision Song Contest 1998]]''<br>''[[Miss World 1999]]''<br>''[[Dancing on Ice (series 2)|Dancing on Ice]]'' (2007)<br>''[[Celebrity Big Brother 6|Celebrity Big Brother]]'' (2009)<br>''[[Ultimate Big Brother]]'' (2010)\n| years_active = 1988\u2013present\n| spouse = {{unbulleted list|{{marriage|John Turnbull|1990|1995|reason=div}}|{{marriage|Lance Gerrard-Wright|2003|2006|reason=div}}|{{marriage|Brian Monet|2008|2019|reason=div}}}}\n| children = 4\n}}\n\n'''Eva Ulrika Jonsson''' (born 16 August 1967)<ref name=biop1/> is a United Kingdom-based Swedish television presenter and model. She became known as a [[TV-am]] weather presenter, moved on to present ''[[Gladiators (1992 UK TV series)|Gladiators]]'', and became a team captain of the show ''[[Shooting Stars (TV series)|Shooting Stars]]''.\n\n==Career==\nAfter working as a secretary, Jonsson began her television career on [[TV-am]] in 1989, as a weather presenter on ''Good Morning, Britain''. From 12 September 1989, she was also the weather presenter for Swedish [[TV3 (Sweden)|TV3]], broadcasting from London. In 1991, she co-presented the short-lived daytime quiz show ''Who's Bluffing Who?'', and starred in the French film, ''[[The Annunciation of Marie]]'' (1991). In 1992, she moved into mainstream presenting and played host to numerous shows including ''[[Gladiators (1992 UK TV series)|Gladiators]]'', ''[[The National Lottery Draws]]'' \u2013 plus two major international broadcasts in 1998 and 1999, the [[Eurovision Song Contest]] and [[Miss World]] respectively. She also modelled for Playtex Lingerie during this period and was a team captain on the BBC TV quiz show ''[[Shooting Stars (TV series)|Shooting Stars]]''.\n\nIn 1997, she interviewed the then British Prime Minister [[John Major]] for the [[BBC Two|BBC 2]] programme, ''The Enormous Election''.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/books/2007/jul/10/media.pressandpublishing Does he mean me?] The Guardian. 10 July 2007</ref> In 1998, she interviewed the then Chancellor of the Exchequer, [[Gordon Brown]], for her programme ''Ulrika in Euroland''.<ref>[http://ftvdb.bfi.org.uk/sift/title/593008?view=cast Cast-ULRIKA IN EUROLAND] British Film Industry (BFI)</ref>\n\nShe presented ''[[Eurovision Song Contest 1998|Eurovision Song Contest]]'' in 1998 when it was hosted in Birmingham, alongside [[Terry Wogan|Sir Terry Wogan]]; later that year she co-hosted the [[Royal Variety Performance]] alongside [[Ronan Keating]] at the [[Lyceum Theatre, London|Lyceum Theatre]] in London.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/230154.stm|title=Spicy Royal Variety Performance|publisher=BBC News|date=8 December 1998|accessdate=25 November 2017}}</ref> Following this, she co-hosted [[Miss World 1999]] with [[Melanie Sykes]] at the [[Olympia Hall]] in London. Jonsson was booked to host [[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]]'s reality game show ''[[Jailbreak (TV series)|Jailbreak]]'' in Autumn 2000 but had to pull out of the project due to health concerns over her newborn child. She was replaced as main host by [[Craig Charles]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/913064.stm|title=Craig Charles to host Jailbreak|website=BBC News|date=6 September 2000|accessdate=20 February 2019}}</ref> Jonsson later presented [[BBC One]] game show ''[[Dog Eat Dog (game show)|Dog Eat Dog]]'', broadcast from April 2001 to November 2002, and ''[[The Joy of Text]]'' in June 2001 alongside [[Terry Alderton]].\n\nIn 2002, Jonsson presented the first series of ITV makeover show ''Home on Their Own'', a show where children made alterations to their house (how they wanted the house to be) during the course of a weekend, while their parents went on holiday. Some of the home improvements included an [[Austin Powers (character)|Austin Powers]] room, individual doorbells for the children and a cinema living room. Johnsson did not return for the second series, which was hosted by [[Tess Daly]] the following year.\n\nIn 2002, she was the subject of a [[Channel 4]] documentary, ''Ulrika Jonsson: the Truth About Men''. The programme featured a candid interview with Jonsson, received heavy press attention and attracted 2.8&nbsp;million viewers.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/media/2002/oct/18/overnights Ulrika confesses to 2.8 million] The Guardian. 18 October 2002</ref>\n\nAfter intense media attention relating to events in her personal life, Jonsson decided to return to Sweden. The Swedish television network [[TV3 (Viasat)|TV3]] offered her the role as hostess of the [[Miss Sweden]] beauty pageant. She accepted the invitation. In March 2003, Jonsson was a contestant on the BBC's ''[[Comic Relief Does Fame Academy]]''. In 2005, she appeared with four other celebrities on [[Channel 4]]'s daytime show ''[[Come Dine with Me]]''. On 20 January 2007, she joined 10 other celebrities to take part in the [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] reality TV show ''[[Dancing on Ice]]'', where she was partnered with [[Pavel Aubrecht]]. With previous skating experience in her native Sweden, Jonsson was expected to go far in the event but finished 9th after being beaten in the skate-off by [[Kay Burley]] during week 3.\n\nOn 20 March 2007, she appeared in the confessional TV show, ''Ulrika: Am I a Sex Addict?'', broadcast on [[Channel 4]]. The show charted Jonsson's personal journey to uncover the truth about [[sex addiction]]. She has appeared on [[BBC One]]'s ''[[Would I Lie to You? (TV series)|Would I Lie To You?]]'' (2007). In March 2009, she appeared in the new ITV series ''[[Piers Morgan's Life Stories]]'', each episode of which included a celebrity figure and a one-to-one interview with [[Piers Morgan|Morgan]] about their lives.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120930222100/http://www.itv.com/PressCentre/PiersMorgansLifeStories/Ep1SharonOsbourneWk09/default.html Piers Morgan's Life Stories] ITV (Press release). 9 February 2009</ref>\n\nIn April 2009, it was confirmed that Jonsson would return to ''[[Shooting Stars (TV series)|Shooting Stars]]'' as team captain for a full series airing later that year.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7980747.stm Shooting Stars back for fresh run] BBC. 3 April 2009</ref> She presented the new series of ''[[BingoLotto (UK)|BingoLotto]]'', on [[Channel One (UK and Ireland)|Virgin 1]] every Sunday night at 7&nbsp;pm which started on 13 September 2009.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090902151140/http://www.bingolotto.tv/consumers/about-bingolotto/ulrika-jonsson/ ULRIKA IS BINGOLOTTO!!!]. Web.archive.org, February 2016</ref>\n\nHer [[debut novel]], ''The Importance of Being Myrtle'', which focuses on relationships<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mandrake/5071917/Rubina-Alis-ad-appearance-with-Nicole-Kidman-tops-film-fee.html Ulrika 'fascinated' by relationships] Daily Telegraph. 29 March 2009</ref> was published by the [[Penguin Group]] on 1 September 2011.\n\nIn 2017, she reached the final of ''[[Celebrity MasterChef]]''.\n\n==''Big Brother''==\nIn January 2009, Jonsson took part in [[Channel 4]]'s ''[[Celebrity Big Brother 6|Celebrity Big Brother]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.channel4.com/bigbrother/housemates/|title=Celebrity Big Brother Cast Page|website=Channel4.com|accessdate=22 January 2018}}</ref> She eventually won with 57% of the final vote during the final on 23 January.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whatsontv.co.uk/reality/celebrity-big-brother-09/news/ulrika-in-celeb-big-brother-pay-row/4633|title=Ulrika in Celeb Big Brother pay row - News - Celebrity Big Brother - What's on TV|date=28 December 2008|website=Whatsontv.co.uk|accessdate=22 January 2018}}</ref><ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/big-brother/4327618/Ulrika-Jonsson-wins-Celebrity-Big-Brother-2009.html Ulrika Jonsson wins Celebrity Big Brother 2009 ] The Telegraph. 24 January 2009</ref> As results were announced to the contestants, Jonsson said \"Oh my god, that's bonkers.\"<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090126215322/http://news.sky.com/skynews/Home/Showbiz-News/Celebrity-Big-Brother-Ulrika-Jonsson-Crowned-2009-Winner/Article/200901415209515?lpos=Showbiz_News_Carousel_Region_4&lid=ARTICLE_15209515_Celebrity_Big_Brother:_Ulrika_Jonsson_Crowned_2009_Winner Ulrika Wins Celebrity Big Brother]. Web.archive.org, February 2016</ref>\n\nShe had been nominated by housemates for eviction on each occasion, firstly by 'head of house' [[Terry Christian]] and then by other housemates, but survived the public vote on five occasions. Jonsson eventually progressed to the finals night, as the only woman left, after [[La Toya Jackson]] was evicted by public vote on Day 20.<ref>[http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/tv_and_radio/article5572742.ece Ulrika Jonsson is last woman in Celebrity Big Brother house] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615153903/http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/tv_and_radio/article5572742.ece |date=15 June 2011 }}</ref> Before her entry into the house, various newspapers had reported that Jonsson had negotiated a \u00a3175,000 payment, nearly eight times as much as some of the other celebrities. Jonsson commented \"It is singularly the weirdest experience of my entire life and I've had quite a weird life.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.channel4.com/bigbrother/news/newsstory.jsp?id=1202|title=upon winning Celebrity Big Brother 2009|website=Channel4.com|accessdate=22 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nJonsson once again entered the Big Brother house on 24 August 2010 for ''[[Ultimate Big Brother]]'', reaching the final and finishing seventh.\n\n==Autobiography and John Leslie scandal==\nJonsson wrote in her 2002 autobiography<ref>{{harv|Jonsson|2002}}</ref> that an unnamed television presenter had raped her earlier in her television career. [[Matthew Wright (television presenter)|Matthew Wright]] named (apparently accidentally) [[John Leslie (TV presenter)|John Leslie]] as the alleged perpetrator on his television show ''[[The Wright Stuff]]''. Jonsson made no public comment on Leslie's naming and did not cooperate with police over the matter. Police investigated Leslie but never charged him with the alleged offence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/3112347.stm|title=Leslie sex charges dropped|date=31 July 2003|accessdate=22 January 2018|website=News.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>  Leslie's career never recovered from the rape allegation.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/personalfinance/fameandfortune/11904194/John-Leslie-I-went-from-350000-a-year-to-nothing-overnight.html |title=John Leslie: 'I went from \u00a3350,000 a year to nothing overnight' |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=4 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nJonsson lives in [[South Moreton]], [[Oxfordshire]].<ref>Maidenhead Advertiser \u2013 [https://web.archive.org/web/20090403094721/http://www.maidenhead-advertiser.co.uk/m/news/article-9452-cookham-celebrity-saved-from-big-brother-eviction/ Cookham celebrity saved from Big Brother eviction], 12 January 2009</ref> She has been married three times and has four children by four fathers.  She is a [[Manchester United]] [[fan (person)|fan]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/profile-almost-one-of-the-lads-ulrika-jonsson-1164830.html | location=London | work=The Independent | first=Vanessa | last=Thorpe | title=Profile: Almost one of the lads; Ulrika Jonsson | date=14 June 1998}}</ref>\n\nShe married cameraman John Turnbull in 1990. They have one son (b.1994). They divorced in 1995.<ref name=\"guardian2011\">Stuart Jeffries, ''[[The Guardian]]'', 27 August 2011, [https://www.theguardian.com/media/2011/aug/27/ulrika-jonsson-phone-hacking Ulrika Jonsson: 'I'm a walking dichotomy']</ref>\n\nJonsson subsequently dated footballer [[Stan Collymore]].<ref name=\"bbc1998\">''[[BBC News]]'', 10 June 1998, [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/110009.stm Sorry for attacking Ulrika - Collymore ']</ref> In June 1998, during the [[1998 World Cup]], Collymore issued a public apology after he was violent towards Jonsson during an argument in a [[Paris]] bar.<ref name=\"bbc1998\"/> Soon after the end of her relationship with Collymore, she began dating German hotel manager Marcus Kempen.<ref name=\"guardian2000\">Hugh Davies, ''[[The Guardian]]'', 11 November 2000, [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1374048/Ulrikas-baby-needs-open-heart-surgery.html Ulrika's baby needs open-heart surgery']</ref> They have one daughter (b.2000).<ref name=\"guardian2000\"/> Jonsson's relationship with Kempen ended soon after the birth.<ref name=\"guardian2011\"/>\n\nIn April 2002, Jonsson confirmed reports that she had had an affair with [[Sven-G\u00f6ran Eriksson]], then manager of England's football team, who had a long-time girlfriend. She stated that her relationship with Eriksson had recently ended.<ref>Vivek Chaudhary, 20 April 2002, [https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2002/apr/20/football.vivekchaudhary Sven 'playing away' with Ulrika], ''[[The Guardian]]''</ref><ref>''[[BBC News]]'', 24 April 2002, [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/1949097.stm Ulrika admits Sven 'relationship']</ref> Partly as a result of her involvement with Eriksson,{{Citation needed|date=March 2020}} she was given the job as a columnist for the ''[[News of the World]]'' newspaper in 2003, in which she regularly commented on Eriksson's personal life. Her column was dropped in 2007,<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/media/2007/sep/19/pressandpublishing.newsoftheworld Full stop for Ulrika's column]. ''[[The Guardian]]'', 19 September 2007.</ref> a year after Eriksson resigned as England manager. It was announced in 2011 that she had taken legal proceedings against the newspaper over allegations that an investigator had [[phone hacking|hacked into her mobile phone]].<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/media/2011/may/17/ulrika-jonsson-phone-hacking-sue?CMP=twt_fd Ulrika Jonsson to sue News of the World over alleged phone hacking]. ''[[The Guardian]]'', 17 May 2011.</ref>\n\nWhile presenting ''Mr. Right'' in 2002, Jonsson met Lance Gerrard-Wright, a contestant on the show. They subsequently began a relationship.<ref name=\"bbc2005\">''[[BBC News]]'', 23 October 2005, [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/4368782.stm Ulrika splits from her Mr Right']</ref> They wed in August 2003. They have one daughter (b.2004).<ref name=\"guardian2011\"/> They separated in October 2005.<ref name=\"bbc2005\"/>\n\nJonsson married her third husband, American advertising executive Brian Monet, in March 2008. They have one son (b.2008). In April 2019, it was announced that they had divorced. She told ''Best'' magazine that they had tried to salvage their relationship with counselling but failed.<ref name=\"Singh\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2140273/Ulrika-Jonsson-introduces-baby-Malcolm.html|title=Ulrika Jonsson introduces baby Malcolm|last=Singh|first=Anita|date=17 June 2008|work=The Telegraph|location=London}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, she went on the dating show ''[[First Dates|First Dates Hotel]]'' and began dating her match on the show, Paul.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.entertainmentdaily.co.uk/tv/entertainment/first-dates-hotel-viewers-thrilled-with-ulrika-jonssons-match/|title=First Dates Hotel viewers thrilled with Ulrika Jonsson's match|date=11 October 2019|website=Entertainment Daily UK|language=en-GB|access-date=17 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n;Television\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- \"\n! Year\n! Programme\n! Role\n|-\n| 1989\u20131992\n| ''Good Morning, Britain'' (TV-am)\n| Weather presenter\n|-\n| 1992\u20132000\n| ''[[Gladiators (1992 UK TV series)|Gladiators]]'' \n| Presenter\n|-\n| 1995\u20132002, 2009\u20132011\n| ''[[Shooting Stars (TV series)|Shooting Stars]]''\n| Team captain\n|-\n| rowspan=2|1998\n| ''[[Eurovision Song Contest 1998|Eurovision Song Contest]]''\n| rowspan=3|Co-presenter\n|-\n| ''[[Royal Variety Performance]]''\n|-\n| 1999\n| ''[[Miss World 1999]]''\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''[[Techno Games]]''\n| rowspan=4|Presenter\n|-\n| 2001\u20132002\n| ''[[Dog Eat Dog (game show)|Dog Eat Dog]]''\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''[[The Joy of Text]]''\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''[[Miss Sweden]]''\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Dancing on Ice]]''\n| Contestant\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Celebrity Big Brother 6|Celebrity Big Brother]]''\n| rowspan=2|Housemate\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Ultimate Big Brother]]''\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Celebrity MasterChef]]''\n| rowspan=2|Contestant\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[First Dates|First Dates Hotel]]''\n|}\n\n;Film\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- \"\n! Year\n! Film\n! Role\n|-\n| 1991\n| ''[[The Annunciation of Marie]]''\n| Violaine Vercors\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[Bob The Builder|Bob the Builder: Snowed Under]]''\n| Jana von Strudel (voice)\n|}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{citation | last=Jonsson | first=Ulrika | year=2002 | title=Honest | publisher=Pan Macmillan | isbn=978-0-330-41174-5 }}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Eurovision Song Contest presenters]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=0429715|name=Ulrika Jonsson}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-media}}\n{{S-new|creation}}\n{{S-ttl|title=Host of ''[[Gladiators (1992 UK TV series)|Gladiators]]''|years=1992\u20132000|regent1=[[John Fashanu]]|years1=1992\u201396, 1999\u20132000|regent2=[[Jeremy Guscott]]|years2=1997\u201398}}\n{{s-non|reason=Show ended.<br /><small> Later [[Gladiators (2008 UK TV series)|revived]] in 2008 with [[Ian Wright]] and [[Kirsty Gallacher]] as hosts.</small>}}\n{{Succession box|\n| before={{flagicon|Ireland}} [[Carrie Crowley]] and [[Ronan Keating]]\n| title=[[List of Eurovision Song Contest presenters|Eurovision Song Contest presenter]]\n| years=<small>(with [[Terry Wogan]])</small><br />[[Eurovision Song Contest 1998|1998]]\n| after={{nowrap|{{flagicon|Israel}} [[Yigal Ravid]], [[Dafna Dekel]] & [[Sigal Shachmon]]}}\n}}\n{{Succession box\n|title=''[[Celebrity Big Brother (UK TV series)|Celebrity Big Brother UK]]'' Winner\n|years=[[Celebrity Big Brother 2009 (UK)|Series 6 (2009)]]\n|before=[[Shilpa Shetty]]\n|after= [[Alex Reid (fighter)|Alex Reid]]\n|}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Big Brother UK}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jonsson, Ulrika}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Sollentuna Municipality]]\n[[Category:Swedish film actresses]]\n[[Category:Swedish television hosts]]\n[[Category:British television presenters]]\n[[Category:Swedish emigrants to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Reality show winners]]\n[[Category:People educated at Burnham Grammar School]]\n[[Category:Secretaries]]\n[[Category:Women television presenters]]\n[[Category:Beauty pageant hosts]]\n[[Category:Swedish female models]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name       = Ulrika Jonsson\n| birth_name = Eva Jonsson<ref name=biop1>{{harv|Jonsson|2003|p=1}}</ref>\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1967|8|16|df=y}}<ref name=biop1/>\n| birth_place = [[Sollentuna Municipality|Sollentuna]], Sweden\n| nationality = Swedish, English\n| other_names = Ulrika Johnson\n| residence = [[South Moreton]], [[Oxfordshire]], England\n| occupation = Actress, television presenter, journalist, novelist\n| television  = ''[[TV-am]]'' (1989\u20131992)<br>''[[Gladiators (1992 UK TV series)|Gladiators]]'' (1992\u20132000)<br>''[[Shooting Stars (TV series)|Shooting Stars]]'' (1995\u20132002, 2009\u20132011)<br>''[[Eurovision Song Contest 1998]]''<br>''[[Miss World 1999]]''<br>''[[Dancing on Ice (series 2)|Dancing on Ice]]'' (2007)<br>''[[Celebrity Big Brother 6|Celebrity Big Brother]]'' (2009)<br>''[[Ultimate Big Brother]]'' (2010)\n| years_active = 1988\u2013present\n| spouse = {{unbulleted list|{{marriage|John Turnbull|1990|1995|reason=div}}|{{marriage|Lance Gerrard-Wright|2003|2006|reason=div}}|{{marriage|Brian Monet|2008|2019|reason=div}}}}\n| children = 4\n}}\n\n'''Eva Ulrika Jonsson''' (born 16 August 1967)<ref name=biop1/> is a United Kingdom-based Swedish television presenter and model. She became known as a [[TV-am]] weather presenter, moved on to present ''[[Gladiators (1992 UK TV series)|Gladiators]]'', and became a team captain of the show ''[[Shooting Stars (TV series)|Shooting Stars]]''.\n\n==Career==\nAfter working as a secretary, Jonsson began her television career on [[TV-am]] in 1989, as a weather presenter on ''Good Morning, Britain''. From 12 September 1989, she was also the weather presenter for Swedish [[TV3 (Sweden)|TV3]], broadcasting from London. In 1991, she co-presented the short-lived daytime quiz show ''Who's Bluffing Who?'', and starred in the French film, ''[[The Annunciation of Marie]]'' (1991). In 1992, she moved into mainstream presenting and played host to numerous shows including ''[[Gladiators (1992 UK TV series)|Gladiators]]'', ''[[The National Lottery Draws]]'' \u2013 plus two major international broadcasts in 1998 and 1999, the [[Eurovision Song Contest]] and [[Miss World]] respectively. She also modelled for Playtex Lingerie during this period and was a team captain on the BBC TV quiz show ''[[Shooting Stars (TV series)|Shooting Stars]]''.\n\nIn 1997, she interviewed the then British Prime Minister [[John Major]] for the [[BBC Two|BBC 2]] programme, ''The Enormous Election''.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/books/2007/jul/10/media.pressandpublishing Does he mean me?] The Guardian. 10 July 2007</ref> In 1998, she interviewed the then Chancellor of the Exchequer, [[Gordon Brown]], for her programme ''Ulrika in Euroland''.<ref>[http://ftvdb.bfi.org.uk/sift/title/593008?view=cast Cast-ULRIKA IN EUROLAND] British Film Industry (BFI)</ref>\n\nShe presented ''[[Eurovision Song Contest 1998|Eurovision Song Contest]]'' in 1998 when it was hosted in Birmingham, alongside [[Terry Wogan|Sir Terry Wogan]]; later that year she co-hosted the [[Royal Variety Performance]] alongside [[Ronan Keating]] at the [[Lyceum Theatre, London|Lyceum Theatre]] in London.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/230154.stm|title=Spicy Royal Variety Performance|publisher=BBC News|date=8 December 1998|accessdate=25 November 2017}}</ref> Following this, she co-hosted [[Miss World 1999]] with [[Melanie Sykes]] at the [[Olympia Hall]] in London. Jonsson was booked to host [[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]]'s reality game show ''[[Jailbreak (TV series)|Jailbreak]]'' in Autumn 2000 but had to pull out of the project due to health concerns over her newborn child. She was replaced as main host by [[Craig Charles]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/913064.stm|title=Craig Charles to host Jailbreak|website=BBC News|date=6 September 2000|accessdate=20 February 2019}}</ref> Jonsson later presented [[BBC One]] game show ''[[Dog Eat Dog (game show)|Dog Eat Dog]]'', broadcast from April 2001 to November 2002, and ''[[The Joy of Text]]'' in June 2001 alongside [[Terry Alderton]].\n\nIn 2002, Jonsson presented the first series of ITV makeover show ''Home on Their Own'', a show where children made alterations to their house (how they wanted the house to be) during the course of a weekend, while their parents went on holiday. Some of the home improvements included an [[Austin Powers (character)|Austin Powers]] room, individual doorbells for the children and a cinema living room. Johnsson did not return for the second series, which was hosted by [[Tess Daly]] the following year.\n\nIn 2002, she was the subject of a [[Channel 4]] documentary, ''Ulrika Jonsson: the Truth About Men''. The programme featured a candid interview with Jonsson, received heavy press attention and attracted 2.8&nbsp;million viewers.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/media/2002/oct/18/overnights Ulrika confesses to 2.8 million] The Guardian. 18 October 2002</ref>\n\nAfter intense media attention relating to events in her personal life, Jonsson decided to return to Sweden. The Swedish television network [[TV3 (Viasat)|TV3]] offered her the role as hostess of the [[Miss Sweden]] beauty pageant. She accepted the invitation. In March 2003, Jonsson was a contestant on the BBC's ''[[Comic Relief Does Fame Academy]]''. In 2005, she appeared with four other celebrities on [[Channel 4]]'s daytime show ''[[Come Dine with Me]]''. On 20 January 2007, she joined 10 other celebrities to take part in the [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] reality TV show ''[[Dancing on Ice]]'', where she was partnered with [[Pavel Aubrecht]]. With previous skating experience in her native Sweden, Jonsson was expected to go far in the event but finished 9th after being beaten in the skate-off by [[Kay Burley]] during week 3.\n\nOn 20 March 2007, she appeared in the confessional TV show, ''Ulrika: Am I a Sex Addict?'', broadcast on [[Channel 4]]. The show charted Jonsson's personal journey to uncover the truth about [[sex addiction]]. She has appeared on [[BBC One]]'s ''[[Would I Lie to You? (TV series)|Would I Lie To You?]]'' (2007). In March 2009, she appeared in the new ITV series ''[[Piers Morgan's Life Stories]]'', each episode of which included a celebrity figure and a one-to-one interview with [[Piers Morgan|Morgan]] about their lives.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120930222100/http://www.itv.com/PressCentre/PiersMorgansLifeStories/Ep1SharonOsbourneWk09/default.html Piers Morgan's Life Stories] ITV (Press release). 9 February 2009</ref>\n\nIn April 2009, it was confirmed that Jonsson would return to ''[[Shooting Stars (TV series)|Shooting Stars]]'' as team captain for a full series airing later that year.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7980747.stm Shooting Stars back for fresh run] BBC. 3 April 2009</ref> She presented the new series of ''[[BingoLotto (UK)|BingoLotto]]'', on [[Channel One (UK and Ireland)|Virgin 1]] every Sunday night at 7&nbsp;pm which started on 13 September 2009.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090902151140/http://www.bingolotto.tv/consumers/about-bingolotto/ulrika-jonsson/ ULRIKA IS BINGOLOTTO!!!]. Web.archive.org, February 2016</ref>\n\nHer [[debut novel]], ''The Importance of Being Myrtle'', which focuses on relationships<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mandrake/5071917/Rubina-Alis-ad-appearance-with-Nicole-Kidman-tops-film-fee.html Ulrika 'fascinated' by relationships] Daily Telegraph. 29 March 2009</ref> was published by the [[Penguin Group]] on 1 September 2011.\n\nIn 2017, she reached the final of ''[[Celebrity MasterChef]]''.\n\n==''Big Brother''==\nIn January 2009, Jonsson took part in [[Channel 4]]'s ''[[Celebrity Big Brother 6|Celebrity Big Brother]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.channel4.com/bigbrother/housemates/|title=Celebrity Big Brother Cast Page|website=Channel4.com|accessdate=22 January 2018}}</ref> She eventually won with 57% of the final vote during the final on 23 January.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whatsontv.co.uk/reality/celebrity-big-brother-09/news/ulrika-in-celeb-big-brother-pay-row/4633|title=Ulrika in Celeb Big Brother pay row - News - Celebrity Big Brother - What's on TV|date=28 December 2008|website=Whatsontv.co.uk|accessdate=22 January 2018}}</ref><ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/big-brother/4327618/Ulrika-Jonsson-wins-Celebrity-Big-Brother-2009.html Ulrika Jonsson wins Celebrity Big Brother 2009 ] The Telegraph. 24 January 2009</ref> As results were announced to the contestants, Jonsson said \"Oh my god, that's bonkers.\"<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090126215322/http://news.sky.com/skynews/Home/Showbiz-News/Celebrity-Big-Brother-Ulrika-Jonsson-Crowned-2009-Winner/Article/200901415209515?lpos=Showbiz_News_Carousel_Region_4&lid=ARTICLE_15209515_Celebrity_Big_Brother:_Ulrika_Jonsson_Crowned_2009_Winner Ulrika Wins Celebrity Big Brother]. Web.archive.org, February 2016</ref>\n\nShe had been nominated by housemates for eviction on each occasion, firstly by 'head of house' [[Terry Christian]] and then by other housemates, but survived the public vote on five occasions. Jonsson eventually progressed to the finals night, as the only woman left, after [[La Toya Jackson]] was evicted by public vote on Day 20.<ref>[http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/tv_and_radio/article5572742.ece Ulrika Jonsson is last woman in Celebrity Big Brother house] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615153903/http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/tv_and_radio/article5572742.ece |date=15 June 2011 }}</ref> Before her entry into the house, various newspapers had reported that Jonsson had negotiated a \u00a3175,000 payment, nearly eight times as much as some of the other celebrities. Jonsson commented \"It is singularly the weirdest experience of my entire life and I've had quite a weird life.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.channel4.com/bigbrother/news/newsstory.jsp?id=1202|title=upon winning Celebrity Big Brother 2009|website=Channel4.com|accessdate=22 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nJonsson once again entered the Big Brother house on 24 August 2010 for ''[[Ultimate Big Brother]]'', reaching the final and finishing seventh.\n\n==Autobiography and John Leslie scandal==\nJonsson wrote in her 2002 autobiography<ref>{{harv|Jonsson|2002}}</ref> that an unnamed television presenter had raped her earlier in her television career. [[Matthew Wright (television presenter)|Matthew Wright]] named (apparently accidentally) [[John Leslie (TV presenter)|John Leslie]] as the alleged perpetrator on his television show ''[[The Wright Stuff]]''. Jonsson made no public comment on Leslie's naming and did not cooperate with police over the matter. Police investigated Leslie but never charged him with the alleged offence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/3112347.stm|title=Leslie sex charges dropped|date=31 July 2003|accessdate=22 January 2018|website=News.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>  Leslie's career never recovered from the rape allegation.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/personalfinance/fameandfortune/11904194/John-Leslie-I-went-from-350000-a-year-to-nothing-overnight.html |title=John Leslie: 'I went from \u00a3350,000 a year to nothing overnight' |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=4 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nJonsson lives in [[South Moreton]], [[Oxfordshire]].<ref>Maidenhead Advertiser \u2013 [https://web.archive.org/web/20090403094721/http://www.maidenhead-advertiser.co.uk/m/news/article-9452-cookham-celebrity-saved-from-big-brother-eviction/ Cookham celebrity saved from Big Brother eviction], 12 January 2009</ref> She has been married three times and has four children by four fathers.  She is a [[Manchester United]] [[fan (person)|fan]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/profile-almost-one-of-the-lads-ulrika-jonsson-1164830.html | location=London | work=The Independent | first=Vanessa | last=Thorpe | title=Profile: Almost one of the lads; Ulrika Jonsson | date=14 June 1998}}</ref>\n\nShe married cameraman John Turnbull in 1990. They have one son (b.1994). They divorced in 1995.<ref name=\"guardian2011\">Stuart Jeffries, ''[[The Guardian]]'', 27 August 2011, [https://www.theguardian.com/media/2011/aug/27/ulrika-jonsson-phone-hacking Ulrika Jonsson: 'I'm a walking dichotomy']</ref>\n\nJonsson subsequently dated footballer [[Stan Collymore]].<ref name=\"bbc1998\">''[[BBC News]]'', 10 June 1998, [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/110009.stm Sorry for attacking Ulrika - Collymore ']</ref> In June 1998, during the [[1998 World Cup]], Collymore issued a public apology after he was violent towards Jonsson during an argument in a [[Paris]] bar.<ref name=\"bbc1998\"/> Soon after the end of her relationship with Collymore, she began dating German hotel manager Marcus Kempen.<ref name=\"guardian2000\">Hugh Davies, ''[[The Guardian]]'', 11 November 2000, [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1374048/Ulrikas-baby-needs-open-heart-surgery.html Ulrika's baby needs open-heart surgery']</ref> They have one daughter (b.2000).<ref name=\"guardian2000\"/> Jonsson's relationship with Kempen ended soon after the birth.<ref name=\"guardian2011\"/>\n\nIn April 2002, Jonsson confirmed reports that she had had an affair with [[Sven-G\u00f6ran Eriksson]], then manager of England's football team, who had a long-time girlfriend. She stated that her relationship with Eriksson had recently ended.<ref>Vivek Chaudhary, 20 April 2002, [https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2002/apr/20/football.vivekchaudhary Sven 'playing away' with Ulrika], ''[[The Guardian]]''</ref><ref>''[[BBC News]]'', 24 April 2002, [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/1949097.stm Ulrika admits Sven 'relationship']</ref> Partly as a result of her involvement with Eriksson,{{Citation needed|date=March 2020}} she was given the job as a columnist for the ''[[News of the World]]'' newspaper in 2003, in which she regularly commented on Eriksson's personal life. Her column was dropped in 2007,<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/media/2007/sep/19/pressandpublishing.newsoftheworld Full stop for Ulrika's column]. ''[[The Guardian]]'', 19 September 2007.</ref> a year after Eriksson resigned as England manager. It was announced in 2011 that she had taken legal proceedings against the newspaper over allegations that an investigator had [[phone hacking|hacked into her mobile phone]].<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/media/2011/may/17/ulrika-jonsson-phone-hacking-sue?CMP=twt_fd Ulrika Jonsson to sue News of the World over alleged phone hacking]. ''[[The Guardian]]'', 17 May 2011.</ref>\n\nWhile presenting ''Mr. Right'' in 2002, Jonsson met Lance Gerrard-Wright, a contestant on the show. They subsequently began a relationship.<ref name=\"bbc2005\">''[[BBC News]]'', 23 October 2005, [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/4368782.stm Ulrika splits from her Mr Right']</ref> They wed in August 2003. They have one daughter (b.2004).<ref name=\"guardian2011\"/> They separated in October 2005.<ref name=\"bbc2005\"/>\n\nJonsson married her third husband, American advertising executive Brian Monet, in March 2008. They have one son (b.2008). In April 2019, it was announced that they had divorced. She told ''Best'' magazine that they had tried to salvage their relationship with counselling but failed.<ref name=\"Singh\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2140273/Ulrika-Jonsson-introduces-baby-Malcolm.html|title=Ulrika Jonsson introduces baby Malcolm|last=Singh|first=Anita|date=17 June 2008|work=The Telegraph|location=London}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, she went on the dating show ''[[First Dates|First Dates Hotel]]'' and began dating her match on the show, Paul.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.entertainmentdaily.co.uk/tv/entertainment/first-dates-hotel-viewers-thrilled-with-ulrika-jonssons-match/|title=First Dates Hotel viewers thrilled with Ulrika Jonsson's match|date=11 October 2019|website=Entertainment Daily UK|language=en-GB|access-date=17 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n;Television\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- \"\n! Year\n! Programme\n! Role\n|-\n| 1989\u20131992\n| ''Good Morning, Britain'' (TV-am)\n| Weather presenter\n|-\n| 1992\u20132000\n| ''[[Gladiators (1992 UK TV series)|Gladiators]]'' \n| Presenter\n|-\n| 1995\u20132002, 2009\u20132011\n| ''[[Shooting Stars (TV series)|Shooting Stars]]''\n| Team captain\n|-\n| rowspan=2|1998\n| ''[[Eurovision Song Contest 1998|Eurovision Song Contest]]''\n| rowspan=3|Co-presenter\n|-\n| ''[[Royal Variety Performance]]''\n|-\n| 1999\n| ''[[Miss World 1999]]''\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''[[Techno Games]]''\n| rowspan=4|Presenter\n|-\n| 2001\u20132002\n| ''[[Dog Eat Dog (game show)|Dog Eat Dog]]''\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''[[The Joy of Text]]''\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''[[Miss Sweden]]''\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Dancing on Ice]]''\n| Contestant\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Celebrity Big Brother 6|Celebrity Big Brother]]''\n| rowspan=2|Housemate\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Ultimate Big Brother]]''\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Celebrity MasterChef]]''\n| rowspan=2|Contestant\n|-\n|2019\n|First Dates Hotel\n|}\n\n;Film\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- \"\n! Year\n! Film\n! Role\n|-\n| 1991\n| ''[[The Annunciation of Marie]]''\n| Violaine Vercors\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[Bob The Builder|Bob the Builder: Snowed Under]]''\n| Jana von Strudel (voice)\n|}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{citation | last=Jonsson | first=Ulrika | year=2002 | title=Honest | publisher=Pan Macmillan | isbn=978-0-330-41174-5 }}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Eurovision Song Contest presenters]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=0429715|name=Ulrika Jonsson}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-media}}\n{{S-new|creation}}\n{{S-ttl|title=Host of ''[[Gladiators (1992 UK TV series)|Gladiators]]''|years=1992\u20132000|regent1=[[John Fashanu]]|years1=1992\u201396, 1999\u20132000|regent2=[[Jeremy Guscott]]|years2=1997\u201398}}\n{{s-non|reason=Show ended.<br /><small> Later [[Gladiators (2008 UK TV series)|revived]] in 2008 with [[Ian Wright]] and [[Kirsty Gallacher]] as hosts.</small>}}\n{{Succession box|\n| before={{flagicon|Ireland}} [[Carrie Crowley]] and [[Ronan Keating]]\n| title=[[List of Eurovision Song Contest presenters|Eurovision Song Contest presenter]]\n| years=<small>(with [[Terry Wogan]])</small><br />[[Eurovision Song Contest 1998|1998]]\n| after={{nowrap|{{flagicon|Israel}} [[Yigal Ravid]], [[Dafna Dekel]] & [[Sigal Shachmon]]}}\n}}\n{{Succession box\n|titl